Part 3:
Brian Cox and Dara O Briain return for their third night celebrating space and astronomy, with more updates from astronaut Tim Peake. They explore what keeps Tim and his International Space Station crew-mates safe in the hazardous environment of space. Brian and Dara also welcome a special guest to take the gravity challenge. Liz Bonnin reports live from the European Astronaut Centre, where she tests whether comedian John Bishop has the 'right stuff'. John will be strapped into a giant centrifuge machine to experience how future astronauts will simulate gravity during deep-space missions. Brian and Dara are joined in the studio by Dame Jocelyn Bell-Burnell to hear how she discovered the first pulsar star, giving astronomers one of their most precious tools for studying the universe. They find out whether Stargazing viewers have discovered any new pulsars, training Jodrell's famous telescope onto them to reveal exactly what has been discovered, and how much that means to astronomers.
